'''Sir Douglas Jardine Flint''', [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]] <ref name="Executives biographies: Douglas Flint - HSBC Board of Directors">{{cite web | url=http://www.hsbc.com/about-hsbc/leadership/douglas-flint | title=Executives biographies: Douglas Flint - HSBC Board of Directors | accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> is a British banking businessman and former Group Chairman of [[HSBC|HSBC Holdings]]. He served from 2010 to 2017, having previously been Group Finance Director since 1995.<ref name="Douglas Flint: HSBC's 'safe pair of hands' - Telegraph">{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/8021791/Douglas-Flint-HSBCs-safe-pair-of-hands.html | title=Douglas Flint: HSBC's 'safe pair of hands' - Telegraph | accessdate=22 July 2016 | author=Harry Wilson}}</ref>
== Biography ==
=== Education === Flint graduated with a bachelor's degree with honours in Accounting from the [[University of Glasgow]]. He also completed the PMD course at Harvard Business School in 1983. Flint is a member of a number of professional bodies such as the [[Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland]], the British [[Association of Corporate Treasurers]] professional body and most recently, [[Institute of International Finance]], where he now serves as Chairman of the Board. He is also a Fellow of the [[Chartered Institute of Management Accountants]].<ref name="Executives biographies: Douglas Flint - HSBC Board of Directors" />
=== Career === Flint started his career in Peat Marwick Mitchell & Co. (now [[KPMG]]), and was appointed a partner of the firm in 1988. He has an in depth knowledge of banking, treasury and securities trading operations, financial reporting of multinationals.{{cn|date=April 2017}} He became Group Finance Director of HSBC in 1995. He was the Chairman of the Financial Reporting Council's review of the [[Turnbull Report|Turnbull Guidance on Internal Control]] from 2004 to 2005 and was a member of The Accounting Standards Board and the Standards Advisory Council of the International Accounting Standards Committee Foundation from 2001 to 2004.<ref name="Executives biographies: Douglas Flint - HSBC Board of Directors" />
In June 2006, in recognition to his services to the finance industry, he was appointed a CBE ([[Order of the British Empire|Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]).<ref name="Wyman and Flint lead honours - Accountancy Age">{{cite web | url=http://www.accountancyage.com/aa/news/1757444/wyman-flint-lead-honours | title=Wyman and Flint lead honours - Accountancy Age | date=21 June 2006 | accessdate=22 July 2016 | author=Kevin Reed}}</ref>
Flint became chairman of HSBC Holdings PLC, Europe's biggest bank, at the end of 2010.<ref name="Douglas Flint takes top job amid HSBC drama - Daily Mail Online">{{cite web | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/money/article-1314686/Douglas-Flint-takes-job-amid-HSBC-drama.html?ito=feeds-newsxml | title=Douglas Flint takes top job amid HSBC drama - Daily Mail Online | publisher=Daily Mail | date=24 September 2010 | accessdate=22 July 2016 | author=Rupert Steiner}}</ref> <ref name="Europe's top bank names new management">{{cite web | url=http://www.smh.com.au//breaking-news-business/europes-top-bank-names-new-management-20100925-15qwq.html | title=Europe's top bank names new management | publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald | date=25 September 2010 | accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> <ref name="Banks plead for guidance on bonuses set to total £7bn - Telegraph">{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/banksandfinance/8234359/Banks-plead-for-guidance-on-bonuses-set-to-total-7bn.html | title=Banks plead for guidance on bonuses set to total £7bn - Telegraph | publisher=The Telegraph | date=2 January 2011 | accessdate=22 July 2016 | author=James Quinn}}</ref> <ref name="Europe's top bank HSBC unveils boardroom shake-up">{{cite web | url=http://www.smh.com.au//breaking-news-world/europes-top-bank-hsbc-unveils-boardroom-shakeup-20100925-15qxd.html | title=Europe's top bank HSBC unveils boardroom shake-up | publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald | date=25 September 2010 | accessdate=22 July 2016 | author=Ben Perry}}</ref> <ref name="HSBC chief Mike Geoghegan ousted after brutal boardroom battle - The Guardian">{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2010/sep/23/hsbc-mike-geohegan-replaced-stuart-gulliver | title=HSBC chief Mike Geoghegan ousted after brutal boardroom battle - The Guardian | publisher=The Guardian | date=24 September 2010 | accessdate=22 July 2016 | author=Jill Treanor}}</ref>
