{{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | name = | image = <!-- include the file, px and alt: [[File:Example.jpg|200px|alt=Cover]] --> | caption = | author = [[David Caplovitz]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = | series = | subject = [[Consumer movement]] | genre = | publisher = Free Press | publisher2 = | pub_date = | english_pub_date = October 1967 | media_type = | pages = | awards = | isbn = 978-0029052501 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Poor Pay More''''' is a 1967 book published by [[David Caplovitz]]. It is a sociology study of what could be called the "[[poverty penalty]]", which is a concept that poor people pay more for the same goods and services as people with more money do.
[[Esther Peterson]] cited the book as being important for understanding contemporary consumer problems.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Goodman|first=Charles S.|title=Do the poor pay more?|journal=Journal of Marketing|date=Jan 1968|volume=32|issue=1|pages=18–24|jstor=1249191|publisher=American Marketing Association|doi=10.2307/1249191}}</ref>
In 2010 a researcher cited the book as still being relevant.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Mierzwinski | first1 = E. | title = Colston E. Warne Lecture: Consumer Protection 2.0-Protecting Consumers in the 21st Century | doi = 10.1111/j.1745-6606.2010.01185.x | journal = Journal of Consumer Affairs | volume = 44 | issue = 3 | pages = 578–597 | year = 2010 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref>
