{{Multiple issues| {{no footnotes|date=January 2016}} {{one source|date=January 2016}} }} {{Infobox officeholder | name = William Brockenbrough | nationality = | image = William Brockenbrough.jpg | office = [[List of Justices of the Supreme Court of Virginia|Justice of the Virginia Supreme Court]] | appointer = | term_start = February 20, 1834 | term_end = December 10, 1838 | birth_date={{birth date|1778|7|10|mf=y}} | birth_place=[[Tappahannock, Virginia]] | death_date={{death date and age|mf=yes|1838|12|10|1778|7|10}} | death_place=[[Richmond, Virginia]] | party= | spouse=[[Judith Brockenbrough|Judith Robinson White]] | religion= | alma_mater = [[College of William and Mary]] | occupation=Lawyer, judge, politician }} '''William Brockenbrough''' (July 10, 1778 – December 10, 1838) was a [[Virginia]] lawyer, political figure and judge of the [[Supreme Court of Virginia|Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals]].
==Biography== Brockenbrough was born in [[Tappahannock, Virginia|Tappahannock]] in [[Essex County, Virginia]], United States, the son of Dr. John Brockenbaugh and Sarah Roane. He attended the [[College of William and Mary]] in 1798. He studied law and then went into private practice. In 1802-03 he represented Essex County in the [[Virginia House of Delegates|House of Delegates]] and became a member of the Council of State in May, 1803. His judicial career started when he was appointed as a judge of the general court on February 7, 1809. On February 20, 1834, he was appointed a judge of the [[Supreme Court of Virginia|Supreme Court of Appeals]] but died just four years later.
In 1806, he married [[Judith Brockenbrough|Judith Robinson White]] and became the father of [[John White Brockenbrough]]. According to family history, [[Dolley Madison]] said, "as a friend I find Mrs. Judith Brockenbrough unequalled." In 1814, following the burning of [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] by Admiral Cockburn, she and Dolley Madison saved what valuables they could from the [[White House]] before taking refuge at the [[The Octagon House (Washington, D.C.)|Octagon House]]. Judith Brockenbrough's initials are scratched on a windowpane in an upstairs bedroom at [[Mount Vernon (plantation)|Mount Vernon]]. William Brockenbrough's home in [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]], at Fifth and Clay streets, was frequently visited by [[John Marshall|Chief Justice Marshall]] and other notable citizens of Richmond.
==Children== One son, John White Brockenbroug married Mary C. Bowyer and became a judge of the United States Court for the Western District of Virginia, founder and head of his own law school at Lexington, Professor in the Law School of Washington and Lee University, member of the [[Confederate States of America]] Congress, and a publisher of law decisions. One daughter, Mary, married another lawyer, Willoughby Newton. Another daughter, named Judith White after her mother, married Episcopal clergyman John P. McQuire and published her diary written during the [[American Civil War]], "The Diary of a Southern Refugee".
