'''William S. Rukeyser''' (born 1939) is an American [[journalist]] who was the founding [[managing editor]] of ''[[Money (magazine)|Money]]'' magazine and [[managing editor]] of ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]''.
==Biography== From its founding in 1998 until 2009 Rukeyser was editorial director of ''[[Corporate Board Member]]'' [[magazine]], aimed at the directors of [[public companies]]. He also has appeared on [[television]] as a financial commentator on [[CNN]] Financial News and [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]].<ref>[http://www.emmyonline.org/emmy/2ndBizEmmyNominees.html 1st Annual Business Emmy Awards<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
He is the son of the late financial journalist [[Merryle S. Rukeyser]] and the younger brother of the late financial journalist and commentator [[Louis Rukeyser]] of ''[[Wall Street Week]]'' fame.
Rukeyser attended [[Princeton University]], graduating with an A.B. degree in 1961. He also studied English literature as a graduate student at [[Christ's College, Cambridge|Christ's College]], [[Cambridge University]].<ref name=CBM>[http://www.boardmember.com/ourpeople.aspx Our People], ''Corporate Board Member'' magazine website, accessed April 19, 2008</ref>
After four years as a ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' reporter in Europe, he started work at [[Time Inc.]] in 1967 as an associate editor of ''Fortune''. In 1968, he signed the "[[Writers and Editors War Tax Protest]]" pledge, vowing to refuse tax payments in protest against the Vietnam War.<ref>"Writers and Editors War Tax Protest" January 30, 1968 ''New York Post''</ref> When ''Money'' was founded in 1972 he became its managing editor, and continued in that position for eight years before returning to ''Fortune'' as its managing editor.<ref name=whittle>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B0DE0DF153EF934A35751C1A961948260 Rukeyser Is Shifting From Time to Whittle], ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 7, 1987</ref> He was abruptly removed from that position in 1986 to make way for Marshall Loeb, of Time magazine. In 1988 he left Time Inc., to become editor in chief for [[Whittle Communications]] in [[Knoxville, Tennessee]].<ref name=whittle/> In 1998 he became editorial director of the new magazine ''Corporate Board Member'', aimed at the directors of public companies.<ref>William B. King, [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa5403/is_/ai_n21425227 Corporate Board Member magazine debuts in August], ''Bank Director'', Third Quarter 1998</ref> He continued in that role until 2009. He continues to devote his time to [[freelance]] [[editing]] and editorial consulting on projects such as ''The Partnership: The Making of Goldman Sachs'' by Charles D. Ellis (Penguin Press, 2008).{{citation needed|date=April 2009}}
Rukeyser and his wife, Elisabeth, are residents of Knoxville, Tennessee, where he is chairman of [[University Health System Inc.]] and past chairman of the Knoxville Jazz Orchestra. He is also a director of the Overseas Press Club Foundation and a member of the advisory board of the Princeton University Press Club.<ref name=CBM/>
